This is a good puzzle I'd like to solve. I think it might be better, though, to output the value that satisfies the expression when it is satisfiable, and/or have a third category for when the expression is universally true.

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: I appreciate this puzzle

Goal
* Please format "AND", "(", ")", "True" and "False" as {{constants}}.

* Please capitalise "True" and "False" for consistency with Input section.

Input
* Please format "TRUE", "FALSE", "AND", "OR" and "XOR" (twice) as {{constants}}.

* Please delete the example.

Output
* Please format "Satisfiable" and "Unsatisfiable" as {{constants}}.

Constraints
* N is greater than 10 in some cases. Please fix the constraint and/or the cases.

Difficulty
* Suggest to change the level from Easy to Medium, considering parsing is required for languages that do not support "eval".

Thanks.

Thank you very much for your helpful feedback! I have applied your suggestions.

Regarding the difficulty, you have a very good point. I did not consider that. I have changed it to Medium.
Thank you for your suggestion. Since I would like the puzzle to be like the full SAT problem, I'd prefer to just output if an expression is satisfiable or not; if that makes sense.

Would you please state the reasons for your approval and not just mention that you accept a contribution in the future?

Also, I notice that you've approved 6 contributions in a row. Have you really tried to solve the contributions and write your own solutions before you approve them? Please don't approve them if you have not done so yet.

Thanks. Only one point is outstanding:

Input
* Please format "AND", "OR" and "XOR" (twice) as {{constants}}.
Oops. Thanks for pointing it out!
